{
  "doc_id": "29760",
  "text": "Endothelial precursor cells (EPCs) are a group of cells with the inherent capacity to differentiate into mature cells [CITATION_1] . Asahara et al [CITATION_2] reported on the isolation of these CD34-positive mononuclear cells from human peripheral blood. EPCs have been indicated to integrate into the capillary-vessel endothelium of rodent hindlimbs induced by ligation of the artery [CITATION_3] . Previous studies also revealed the potency of EPCs in the treatment of endothelial dysfunction induced by diabetes [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, compared with those in healthy subjects, EPC counts were lower, and the function was also disturbed in patients with either type of DM [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . The development of strategies to improve the counts and activity of EPCs in patients with DM is a major focus in the field of autologous cell therapy. As EPCs from patients with diabetes exhibit different behaviors compared with those from healthy subjects, several different approaches have been investigated to restore their dysregulation and dysfunction by targeting specific sites [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] .",
